label.name: Source of description
label.description: Source of item description. This should be a formal citation if possible. For informal sources a narrative description is acceptable.

label.name: Georeference
label.description: Coordinates documenting the location of the item

label.name: Date
label.description: A point or period of time associated with an event in the life cycle of the resource.

label.name: Library of Congress Subject Headings
label.description: Library of Congress Subject headings describing this object. To add a new heading simply type the first few letters of the heading and choose the desired one from the displayed list of possible matches.

label.name: Alternate identifiers
label.description: Any additional unambiguous reference to the resource within a given context.

label.name: GeoNames
label.description: A Geographic lookup that takes search text, passes it to the GeoNames search service and provides a drop down with search results (ordered by score). Selected geoname is stored as both text (name, country, continent and ID) and the service URL identifier.

label.name: Rights
label.description: Information about rights held in and over the resource.

label.name: Source
label.description: A related resource from which the described resource is derived.

label.name: Computer Based Presentation Environment
label.description: Computer environment the work has been optimized for.

label.name: Software Subsidiary
label.description: Plugins such as media players and drivers for peripheral devices.

label.name: Production History
label.description: If it was made from a component you hold please state its component number, if it was made from a component made by the artist or gallery please give details of the production of the work and what this component was made from. For example, the work of art was edited from miniDV footage on Final Cut Pro and output to DVCAM from which this component was made.

label.name: Do you want the work to last?
What do you think about the preservation of your work?
How would you feel about a re-installation of your work, either here at the MF or somewhere else?

In regard to the specific materials you've chosen for your work, how do you feel about their preservation? Would the substitution of any material for one with a similar look/feel impact your understanding of the work's authenticity?
What goes into your selection of materials?
If the materials selected are essential to the work, what are the qualities that you were looking for?
What about the display quality (image stillness, color v. black and white, size of screen/display box) is essential to your work?
How does the positioning of the work's elements play into the work?
